type="user">jms-00KT</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00KT.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Counting bijections between finite sets">Counting <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijections</fr:link> between finite sets</fr:title><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For all finite sets <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we have:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Bij}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =  \begin {cases}   0 &\text {if } \mathord {\#}{A}\not =\mathord {\#}{B}\\   n!&\text {if } \mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}=n  \end {cases} ]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1689</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#394</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-394.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00KT</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> between two sets is a way of associating <fr:em>precisely</fr:em> one element of the first set with <fr:em>precisely one</fr:em> element of the second set. These associations are embodied in the functions <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\to  A]]></fr:tex>, and the uniqueness of the associations is expressed by the conditio that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> be simultaneously a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KS.xml"
addr="jms-00KS"
title="Section-retraction pair">section</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KS.xml"
addr="jms-00KS"
title="Section-retraction pair">retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. Two sets of different cardinality can not be associated in this way, because there would always be left over elements that are not associated to any corresponding element. In this way, we see that a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> exists between two sets if and only if they have the same cardinality.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Assuming two finite sets <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A,B]]></fr:tex> with cardinality <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}=n]]></fr:tex>, we must now count precisely how many bijections there are from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. To construct such a bijection, we put all the elements <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> into a pile. Then, for each element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> we must successively choose and then <fr:em>discard</fr:em> an element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>; we have to discard the element because we are not allowed to choose it again (for, if we did, the association would not be bijective). At the beginning (“round <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k=0]]></fr:tex>”</html:span>), there are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> many choices we could make; in the next round <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k=1]]></fr:tex>, there are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex> many choices that we could make; in the <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>th</html:span> round, there are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n-k]]></fr:tex> many choices that we could make. At the very end (after the <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n-1]]></fr:tex>th</html:span> round), we shall have constructed a bijection after making <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n! = \prod _{0\leq  k<n} n-k]]></fr:tex> choices in total. Thus the number of distinct bijections from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n!]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
