addr="jms-00L0"
title="Isomorphic sets">isomorphic sets</fr:link></fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> between finite sets is just a “relabeling” of its elements: for example, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{0,1\right \}\mathclose {}}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{\mathsf {false},\mathsf {true}\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Isomorphism of infinite sets can be more confusing: for example, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{n:\mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,n>0\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {N}\times \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and even <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}\right )\mathclose {}}\cong \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
