text="Bijection">Bijection</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KF.xml"
addr="jms-00KF"
title="Function">function</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>bijective</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>bijection</fr:strong></fr:em> whenever there exists a (necessarily unique) function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\to  A]]></fr:tex> (referred to as the <fr:em><fr:strong>inverse</fr:strong></fr:em> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>) that is simultaneously a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KS.xml"
addr="jms-00KS"
title="Section-retraction pair">retraction</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KS.xml"
addr="jms-00KS"
title="Section-retraction pair">section</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> in the sense that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\circ  f=\mathsf {id}_{A}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\circ  g = \mathsf {id}_{B}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We will often write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}\colon  B\to  A]]></fr:tex> for the inverse to a bijection <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
